## CATEGORY 2 — CODE QUALITY
------------------------------

[CRITICAL] CQ-001 — Bare `except:` clauses swallow all exceptions silently
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:19, visionlog/visionlog.py:33
  Detail  : Both `get_public_ip` and `get_geo_info` use bare `except:` blocks
            that catch all exceptions including `KeyboardInterrupt`,
            `SystemExit`, and `MemoryError`. Network failures, timeouts, and
            JSON parsing errors are silently discarded. This masks real bugs and
            makes diagnosing issues in production impossible.
  Action  : Replace with `except (requests.RequestException, KeyError, ValueError):`
            and log a warning before returning the fallback value. Consider
            using `requests.exceptions.Timeout` with explicit timeouts.

[WARNING] CQ-002 — No request timeouts on external HTTP calls
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:18, visionlog/visionlog.py:25
  Detail  : Calls to `api64.ipify.org` and `ipinfo.io` have no `timeout`
            parameter. In production, this can cause indefinite hangs when the
            external service is slow or unreachable, blocking the calling thread.
  Action  : Add `timeout=5` (or a configurable value) to all `requests.get`
            calls.

[WARNING] CQ-003 — `add_common_fields` hardcodes "visionlog" as `app_name`
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:54
  Detail  : The `app_name` field is always set to "visionlog" regardless of the
            `service_name` argument passed to `get_logger`. This produces
            misleading metadata for any caller that passes their own service
            name.
  Action  : Either remove the hardcoded default or propagate `service_name`
            into `add_common_fields` via a closure or structlog context variable.

[WARNING] CQ-004 — Structlog `cache_logger_on_first_use=True` conflicts with dynamic binding
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:91
  Detail  : With `cache_logger_on_first_use=True`, the processor chain is frozen
            after the first log call. Calling `logger.bind(...)` after the first
            use will silently have no effect. This is a known structlog gotcha.
  Action  : Set `cache_logger_on_first_use=False` or document the limitation
            clearly. For most single-call `get_logger` usages this is fine, but
            it should be explicit.

[WARNING] CQ-005 — loguru is imported but functionally unused
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:3, visionlog/visionlog.py:78-79
  Detail  : loguru is listed as a dependency and imported, but the only use is
            removing the default sink and adding a `sys.stdout` sink without any
            format. structlog is then used as the actual logging facade. The
            loguru setup has no visible effect on the output and adds confusion.
  Action  : Either remove loguru entirely (and the related setup code) or
            explicitly integrate it as a structlog renderer backend. If loguru
            is kept, document its role.

[MINOR]   CQ-006 — `get_logger` reconfigures structlog globally on every call
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:81-91
  Detail  : `structlog.configure(...)` is called every time `get_logger()` is
            invoked. This mutates a global singleton and is not thread-safe.
            In multi-threaded applications, concurrent calls to `get_logger()`
            can produce inconsistent processor chains.
  Action  : Call `structlog.configure` once at module import time, not inside
            `get_logger`. Move logger construction (binding) into a separate
            helper if needed.

[MINOR]   CQ-007 — `__init__.py` exports only one symbol without `__all__`
  Files   : visionlog/__init__.py
  Detail  : The public API is not declared explicitly. Without `__all__`, any
            symbol imported at module level becomes part of the public API,
            making it easy to accidentally expose internal helpers.
  Action  : Add `__all__ = ["get_logger"]` to `visionlog/__init__.py`.

## CATEGORY 3 — TYPING & INTERFACES
--------------------------------------

[CRITICAL] TYP-001 — `ip_address` parameter type is incorrect
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:62
  Detail  : The parameter is declared as `ip_address: Optional[str] = None`
            but the code explicitly handles the case where `ip_address is True`
            (line 103). `Optional[str]` does not include `bool`, so type
            checkers will flag this as unreachable and callers will not know
            they can pass `True`.
  Action  : Change the type annotation to `Union[bool, str, None]` and update
            the docstring example to match.

[WARNING] TYP-002 — Return types missing on all public functions
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py (all functions), visionlog/cli.py
  Detail  : None of the functions have return type annotations. This limits
            IDE autocompletion, makes the public API harder to understand, and
            prevents mypy from catching type errors.
  Action  : Add return type annotations:
            - `serialize_json` → `str`
            - `get_public_ip` → `Optional[str]`
            - `get_geo_info` → `Dict[str, str]`
            - `get_device_info` → `Dict[str, str]`
            - `add_common_fields` → `Dict[str, Any]`
            - `get_logger` → `structlog.stdlib.BoundLogger`

[WARNING] TYP-003 — No `py.typed` marker file
  Files   : visionlog/
  Detail  : PEP 561 requires a `py.typed` marker file for packages that
            distribute inline type information. Without it, mypy and pyright
            will ignore the type hints when the package is installed.
  Action  : Create an empty `visionlog/py.typed` file and add
            `include = ["visionlog/py.typed"]` to pyproject.toml.

[MINOR]   TYP-004 — No mypy or pyright configuration
  Files   : pyproject.toml
  Detail  : There is no `[tool.mypy]` or `pyrightconfig.json` section. Static
            type checking cannot be consistently run without a baseline
            configuration.
  Action  : Add a `[tool.mypy]` section to `pyproject.toml` with at minimum:
            `strict = false`, `ignore_missing_imports = true`, and
            `python_version = "3.8"`.

