## CATEGORY 9 — DEPENDENCIES
------------------------------

[CRITICAL] DEP-001 — Privacy risk: automatic IP collection without consent
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:15-20, 58-66
  Detail  : The library can automatically collect and attach the caller's
            public IP address to every log line. IP addresses are Personally
            Identifiable Information (PII) under GDPR, CCPA, and similar
            regulations. There is no privacy notice, consent mechanism, or
            documentation of this behaviour.
  Action  : At minimum, set `ip_address` default to `None` (it already is),
            but add explicit docstring warnings about PII implications. Consider
            adding a `privacy_mode: bool = True` flag that disables all PII
            enrichment (IP, geo, device) by default.

[WARNING] DEP-002 — `device-detector` is a heavy dependency for an optional feature
  Files   : pyproject.toml:21, visionlog/visionlog.py:8
  Detail  : `device-detector` (PyPI: `device-detector`) bundles large YAML
            device databases. It is only used when `device_info=True` or
            `user_agent` is provided. Making all users pay this install cost
            unconditionally is poor library design.
  Action  : Make `device-detector` an optional extra:
            `[tool.poetry.extras]`
            `device = ["device-detector"]`
            Guard the import with a try/except and raise `ImportError` with
            install instructions when the user enables `device_info=True`.

[WARNING] DEP-003 — `requests` is a heavy transitive dependency; no timeout hardening
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:6
  Detail  : The `requests` library adds significant install weight for a
            logging utility. The two HTTP calls it makes have no timeout.
            For a logging library that should have minimal overhead, using the
            stdlib `urllib.request` would be lighter.
  Action  : Consider replacing `requests` with stdlib `urllib.request` for
            the two simple GET calls, or at minimum add `timeout=` parameters
            and document the network dependency.

[MINOR]   DEP-004 — No upper bound on structlog version
  Files   : pyproject.toml:16
  Detail  : `structlog = "^23.1.0"` allows any 23.x or 24.x version. Major
            structlog releases (e.g., 24.x) may contain breaking API changes.
            Poetry's `^` operator handles this correctly for semantic
            versioning, but the constraint should be reviewed if structlog
            makes a breaking 24.0 release.
  Action  : Monitor structlog releases and update the constraint after
            compatibility testing.

## CATEGORY 10 — PRODUCTION READINESS
---------------------------------------

[CRITICAL] PROD-001 — Library is not safe to use in production
  Files   : (all)
  Detail  : The combination of zero tests, no CI, swallowed exceptions, a
            broken type annotation (ip_address: Optional[str] when True is
            also accepted), unused dependencies, and undocumented PII
            collection makes this library unsuitable for production use.
  Action  : Address CRITICAL findings (TST-001, TEST-001, CICD-001, CQ-001,
            TYP-001, DEP-001) before considering any production deployment.

[WARNING] PROD-002 — No logging of internal errors
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py
  Detail  : Failures in `get_public_ip()` and `get_geo_info()` are silently
            discarded. In production, operators need to know when enrichment
            is degraded (e.g., geo-lookup service is down).
  Action  : Log a warning (using Python's stdlib `warnings.warn` or the
            logger itself) when an enrichment step fails, so operators can
            detect degraded enrichment without crashing the application.

[WARNING] PROD-003 — No graceful degradation documentation
  Files   : README.md, visionlog/visionlog.py
  Detail  : The library makes outbound network calls during logger creation.
            There is no documentation of what happens in air-gapped
            environments, firewalled containers, or offline CI runners.
  Action  : Document all network calls and their fallback behaviour. Add a
            `disable_network=True` parameter to `get_logger` that skips all
            HTTP enrichment.

